"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885382","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Government plans to publish a world leading Resources and Waste Strategy by the end of the year.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-23T11:09:00.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885382/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885382/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-17","Waste Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the Government plans to publish its Waste and Resources Review; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","136245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885383","Department for International Trade","false","2018-04-25","<p>The Secretary of State for International Trade and his Ministerial team undertake regular visits overseas to promote trade and investment. The programmes typically include bilateral meetings with counterparts to discuss trade cooperation and meetings with business leaders and investors.</p><p>It would be disproportionate to publish the detail of each of the 60 visits, but by way of example, the Secretary of State led a delegation of more than 50 UK businesses to China, during the Prime Minister's visit. During the visit he witnessed the signing of a number of commercial deals, addressed business leaders at a Digital China event and attended a China-UK Business Forum.</p><p>The Department for International Trade do publish details of Ministerial visits before and during visits through press releases and social media.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-04-25T16:50:54.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885383/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885383/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-04-17","Trade Remedies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 22 March to Question 132109 on trade remedies, if he will publish the schedule of meetings which took place at each of the 60 visits.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","136246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885384","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Home Office visa case-working system does not capture the profession of the applicant or which UK Region within the NHS they wish to work in. This information is captured on the Tier 2 application form, however, to provide that information would require a manual check of our records and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","136248","2018-04-23T09:09:54.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885384/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885384/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Visas: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 16 April 2018 to Questions 134800, 134801, 134802, 134803 and 134804, on Visas: Skilled Workers, if she will publish the data requested.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","136247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885385","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Home Office visa case-working system does not capture the profession of the applicant or which UK Region within the NHS they wish to work in. This information is captured on the Tier 2 application form, however, to provide that information would require a manual check of our records and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","136247","2018-04-23T09:09:54.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885385/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885385/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Visas: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department holds the data requested in Questions 134800, 134801, 134802, 134803 and 134805.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","136248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885386","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Environment Agency’s latest Waste Management in England Statistics show that 11.64 million tonnes of waste were incinerated in England in 2016, compared to a permitted capacity of 15.48 million tonnes. For operational incinerators in the East of England only, those figures were 1.19 million tonnes incinerated compared to 1.42 million tonnes of capacity.</p><p> </p><p>There are several reasons for the difference between throughput and permitted capacity. The permitted capacity relates to the waste managed at the site and not the actual throughput of the facility as the site might have more than one processing facility. Throughput will also vary depending on the wastes heat value, its composition, the maintenance regime of the facility and the delivery of waste from clients. To allow for these variances permitted capacity is normally higher than the actual processing capacity. It would not be financially viable for plants to run under capacity.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-23T14:29:25.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885386/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885386/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-17","Incinerators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2017 to Question 117198, on Incinerators, for what reason the UK's on-stream incineration capacity is underused compared with the permitted capacity; and for what reason there is a similar difference in the East of England.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","136249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885387","Treasury","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is the international standard-setting body for Anti-Money laundering (AML) and countering the financing of terrorism (CFT). The FATF Plenary, its decision-making body, meets three times a year.</p><p> </p><p>Due to the sensitive nature of Plenary discussions, agendas are not made public ahead of meetings. As is usual, following the June Plenary we will place a letter in the House library to update on developments at FATF.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-04-23T12:27:41.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885387/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885387/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-17","Financial Action Task Force","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the agenda for the Financial Action Task Force plenary meeting in June 2018.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","136250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885388","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-23","<p>The 25 Year Environment Plan sets out our commitment to make it easier for people to recycle and to increase the quantity and quality of materials collected. Through the Framework for Greater Consistency, the Waste and Resources Action Programme is working with industry and local authorities to promote improved recycling performance and to ensure that a consistent set of core materials are collected by all local authorities. We want to accelerate this process and want householders to benefit from having comprehensive waste and recycling collections which ensure that products are recycled as much as possible and high quality materials are returned to the economy. We will set out measures to support this in our Resources and Waste Strategy to be published later this year.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-23T14:33:27.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885388/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885388/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-17","Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government plans to take to promote the recycling of waste instead of using (a) landfill and (b) incineration.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","136251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885389","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>Data is no longer provided in the format requested. Published data on sponsorship applications can be found in the immigration statistics release.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employer-sponsorship-restricted-certificate-allocations/allocations-of-restricted-certificates-of-sponsorship" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employer-sponsorship-restricted-certificate-allocations/allocations-of-restricted-certificates-of-sponsorship</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-23T09:10:04.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885389/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885389/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Engineers and Scientists: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 29 March 2018 to Question 134308 on Engineers and Scientists: Visas, if she will place that data in the Library.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","136252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885390","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-04-25","<p>VisitBritain and VisitEngland do not hold a breakdown of spending at local level, however London features in many of VisitBritain’s campaign, such as the current global marketing campaign ‘I Travel For’ to increase inbound tourism to Great Britain.</p><p> </p><p>VisitBritain also work with travel and tourism partners such as Sony Pictures and Studio Canal, to promote filming locations across London, and Barclays Premier League to convert football fans to visitors, promoting London stadia and their surrounding neighbourhoods. VisitBritain also work closely with London and Partners to ensure complementary marketing campaigns, including investing £500,000 in London &amp; Partners’ Autumn Season campaign.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, London-based Destination Management Organisations (DMOs) collaborate with other DMOs across the country as part of several VisitEngland Discover England Fund projects.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-04-25T14:10:37.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885390/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885390/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-04-17","Tourism: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of tourism funding from the public purse was allocated to London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","136253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885391","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-25","<p>There have been nine investigations into breaches of section 1112 of the Companies Act 2006 by Companies House, one of which involved multiple companies. Following these investigations Companies House referred three cases to prosecutors. Two of the companies involved in those cases have now been dissolved.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-04-25T15:50:33.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885391/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885391/answer","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885391/answer/previousversion/53560","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-04-17","Company Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many investigations of breaches of section 1112 of the Companies Act 2006 have been undertaken by Companies House; and how many of those investigations (a) led to companies being dissolved and taken off the register and (b) resulted in Companies House referring the case to prosecutors.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","136254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885392","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-25","<p>This information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England publishes quarterly performance data on cancelled elective operations, which includes national, regional and provider level activity, and this can be accessed at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cancelled-elective-operations/cancelled-ops-data/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cancelled-elective-operations/cancelled-ops-data/</a></p><p> </p><p>Data for quarter 3 (October – December 2017) was published on 8 February 2018 with quarter 4 (January – March 2018) due for release on 10 May 2018. This includes figures for those last minute cancellations where the provider did not offer an alternative admission date within 28 days.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-04-25T11:14:44.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885392/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885392/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-17","Surgery: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many elective operations were cancelled in (a) November 2017, (b) December 2017 and (c) January 2018; and how many and what proportion of those operations have not yet been rearranged.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","136255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885393","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-25","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>It was recommended by National Health Service clinical leaders (National Emergency Pressures Panel) that non-urgent elective care be deferred to 31 January (from end of December) to free up capacity for our sickest patients. This deferment of non-urgent operations was the right thing to do while we managed the additional pressures of winter. For those patients who have not had new appointments, cancelled operations should be rescheduled by trusts at the earliest opportunity, taking into account patients’ clinical need.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on scaling up and down bed capacity to respond to demand are managed locally by trusts. During the winter period, over 2,600 additional beds have been made available.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","136257","2018-04-25T15:49:04.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885393/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885393/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-17","Hospital Wards: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many wards are currently closed under the framework to support winter pressures in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","136256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885394","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-25","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>It was recommended by National Health Service clinical leaders (National Emergency Pressures Panel) that non-urgent elective care be deferred to 31 January (from end of December) to free up capacity for our sickest patients. This deferment of non-urgent operations was the right thing to do while we managed the additional pressures of winter. For those patients who have not had new appointments, cancelled operations should be rescheduled by trusts at the earliest opportunity, taking into account patients’ clinical need.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on scaling up and down bed capacity to respond to demand are managed locally by trusts. During the winter period, over 2,600 additional beds have been made available.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","136256","2018-04-25T15:49:04.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885394/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885394/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-17","Surgery: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the average length of time taken was to rearrange elective procedures that were cancelled as a result of the winter pressures.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","136257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885395","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-04-23","<p>The data on the average length of custodial sentence for every offence given by every magistrate court in England and Wales is not produced or published. The Ministry of Justice analyses court performance and custodial sentence lengths in other ways.</p><p> </p><p>Magistrates’ Court data, for period ending December 2016 is published at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/614427/magistrates-court-tool-2016.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/614427/magistrates-court-tool-2016.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>The most recent figures (year ending September 2017) for average custodial sentence length by offence type can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-september-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-september-2017</a></p><p>Please see overview table 5.2c (this table covers both magistrates’ and Crown Courts).</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-04-23T15:44:54.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885395/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885395/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-04-17","Custodial Treatment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will publish the average length of custodial sentence for each type of offence given by each magistrate court in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","136258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885396","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-04-23","<p>The number of defendants remanded in custody by offence group and local justice area in England and Wales in 2016 (latest data currently available) can be viewed in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>Court proceedings data for 2017 are planned for publication in May 2018.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-04-23T15:50:21.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885396/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885396/answer","PQ 136259 table - final.xlsx","PQ 136259 table - final.xlsx","Table for PQ 136259","Table for PQ 136259","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885396/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-04-17","Remand in Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average number of defendants being remanded in custody was by each type of offence for each magistrate court in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","136259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885397","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Government’s mandate to NHS England for 2018-19 continues to set NHS England an objective to maintain and improve performance against core patient access standards. This includes a clear expectation that the statutory referral to treatment standard should be met.</p><p> </p><p>The Government expects NHS England and NHS Improvement to deliver the actions in the NHS Planning Guidance for 2018-19 as key steps towards fully recovering performance against these standards.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-04-23T09:38:48.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885397/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885397/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-17","Hospitals: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the timetable is for the NHS to meet the target for referral to treatment in less than 18 weeks.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","136260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885398","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>‘The Government's mandate to NHS England for 2018-19’ sets out that aggregate performance in accident and emergency departments in England should be above 90% in September 2018, with the majority of trusts meeting 95% in March 2019 and aggregate performance in England at 95% within the course of 2019.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-04-23T09:44:58.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885398/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885398/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-17","Accident and Emergency Departments: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the timetable is for the NHS next to meet its target relating to A&E waiting times of less than four hours.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","136261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885399","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>We are working with departments across government, in close coordination with the Department for Exiting the European Union, to carry out a programme of work to inform our negotiating position with the EU and our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks.</p><p> </p><p>Where appropriate, an impact assessment often accompanies major bills and regulations to illustrate the effects of the changes. For example, the government published an Impact Assessment alongside the EU (Withdrawal) Bill. We will continue publishing Impact Assessments to accompany legislation, where appropriate.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-24T09:09:14.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885399/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885399/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department has conducted any impact assessments on the effect on the British education system of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","136262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885400","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring leaving the European Union is a success for the health and social care sector as well as the United Kingdom as a whole.</p><p> </p><p>Impact Assessments, typically related to specific new primary legislation before Parliament, are narrowly defined. For example, the Government laid an impact assessment alongside the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill, which can be found on our website through the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/628004/2017-07-12_repeal_bill_impact_assessment__1_.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/628004/2017-07-12_repeal_bill_impact_assessment__1_.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Civil servants conduct any Impact Assessments related to legislation as business as usual. All policy teams in my Department have conducted assessments of the implications of Brexit and continue to plan for all scenarios.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-04-23T12:29:57.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885400/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885400/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-17","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has conducted any impact assessments on the effect on the healthcare system in the UK of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","136263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885401","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>The 2016 Hate Crime Action Plan set out a number of Home Office and cross-Government actions to tackle online hate crime, including engagement with industry. We will be refreshing the action plan this year.</p><p>The Government has already gone further than these actions: in October 2017 the Home Secretary announced funding for a national online hate crime hub that will help the police to manage online cases more effectively and efficiently; we have successfully worked with industry and partners internationally to agree the removal of illegal hate speech within 24 hours through the EU Commission Code of Conduct on Illegal Hate Speech; and we will publish the Government response to the Internet Safety Strategy consultation in the spring which will set out details on a comprehensive new social media code of practice.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-04-23T16:53:34.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885401/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885401/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Hate Crime: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 28 March 2018 to Question 133769, what specific steps her Department is taking to encourage social media companies to tackle online hate crime.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","136264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885402","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-23","<p>As the Prime Minister has said, “Brexit will not mean a lowering of environmental standards”. We constantly assess our policies against this objective. The EU (Withdrawal) Bill will ensure that the whole body of existing EU environmental law continues to have effect in UK law.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-23T09:41:13.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885402/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885402/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-17","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department has made an assessment of the effect on the environment of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","136265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885403","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>The UK is considering its future migration, mobility and asylum relationships with other states post-Brexit. We hope to continue to cooperate on the issue of migration and build upon the relationships we already have.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-24T15:54:22.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885403/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885403/answer","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885403/answer/previousversion/53507","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-17","EU Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government plans to negotiate bilateral alternatives to the EU Mobility Partnerships.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","136266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885404","Department for Education","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Department for Education funds English for Speakers of Other Languages (ESOL) courses through the adult education budget. We do not collect data on learners that would allow us to identify them as refugees. We have previously published providers’ overall spending on ESOL, which includes funding for refugee learners. I refer the hon. Member for Birmingham, Hall Green to the answer my right hon. Friend, the Minister for Apprentices and Skills gave on 12 March 2018 to <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-03-12/131906/" target="_blank">131906</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, as part of the Home Office’s Vulnerable Person Resettlement Scheme (VPRS) and Vulnerable Children Resettlement Programme (VCRP), local authorities receive £8520 per person for the first year of resettlement (with the exception of Northern Ireland, where the tariff is £8000 per person) from which they are required to provide a range of support services, including access to English language support. Local authorities are able to determine for themselves how this tariff funding is used, based on local need and service provision.</p><p> </p><p>The government has also made an additional £10 million available over five years for English language support for those resettled on the VPRS and VCRP programmes. This funding is for the provision of ESOL classes, and equates to £850 per adult resettled. The Home Office has also allocated funding (£600,000 in each of the financial years 2016/17, 2017/18 and 2018/19, and £500,000 in 2019/20) to enable local authorities to provide additional childcare to those on the VPRS and VCRS so that they can attend ESOL classes.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-04-23T15:12:37.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885404/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885404/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","English Language: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 16 March to Question 134845 on English Language: Refugees, how much funding the Government has allocated to accredited English language teaching for refugees in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","136267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885405","Treasury","false","2018-04-23","<p>The government are determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum and Living Wage (NMW) receives it.</p><p> </p><p>The ‘National Living Wage’ is a rate for workers aged 25 and over which was introduced in April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) review all complaints that are referred to them.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the honourable member to the answer provided at <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;use-dates=True&amp;answered-from=2018-02-01&amp;answered-to=2018-02-28&amp;member=4425&amp;uin=126663" target="_blank">UIN 126663</a> for information on prosecution results.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-04-23T15:39:49.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885405/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885405/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-17","Living Wage: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many employers in Wales were prosecuted for non-payment of the national living wage in each quarter of 2017.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","136268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885406","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>Local councils supply data on the number of children’s centres in England through the Department for Education’s “Get Information about Schools” (GIAS) database at: <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold data on the number of children using children’s centres or the type of services offered through children’s centres centrally. This data is held at a local area level.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","136271 ; 136272","2018-04-24T08:10:50.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885406/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885406/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many Sure Start children’s centres there are there in England.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","136269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885407","Department for Education","false","2018-04-23","<p>The department announced its preferred bidder for the Reception Baseline Assessment on 11 April. As government commercial procedure dictates, the contract for the Reception Baseline Assessment will be uploaded to Contracts Finder once contract award is complete. Information about the number of applications will be included in the contract award notice.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-23T14:52:15.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885407/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885407/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Primary Education: Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will publish the organisations that submitted applications to run the Reception Baseline Assessment.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","136270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885408","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>Local councils supply data on the number of children’s centres in England through the Department for Education’s “Get Information about Schools” (GIAS) database at: <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold data on the number of children using children’s centres or the type of services offered through children’s centres centrally. This data is held at a local area level.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","136269 ; 136272","2018-04-24T08:10:51.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885408/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885408/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the number of children using Sure Start Children's Centres in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","136271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885409","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>Local councils supply data on the number of children’s centres in England through the Department for Education’s “Get Information about Schools” (GIAS) database at: <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold data on the number of children using children’s centres or the type of services offered through children’s centres centrally. This data is held at a local area level.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","136269 ; 136271","2018-04-24T08:10:51.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885409/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885409/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of Sure Start centres offer a referral-only service.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","136272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885410","Cabinet Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and is only available at disproportionate cost.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-04-23T14:54:46.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885410/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885410/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-04-17","Cabinet Office: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which (a) external data analysts and (b) data collection companies his Department has used in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","136273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885411","Treasury","false","2018-04-23","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>HMT routinely records contracts let, where the total contract value is of £10,000 (excl VAT) or more on the Tender and Contract Database.</p><p> </p><p>While the database does retain details of individual suppliers it does not categorise them according to their status e.g. whether they are data analysts and / or data collection companies</p><p> </p><p>To ascertain the information requested would involve drilling down into the information contained and a call out to all individual suppliers to ascertain their formal status at disproportionate cost.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-04-23T14:07:15.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885411/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885411/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-17","Treasury: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which (a) external data analysts and (b) data collection companies his Department has used in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","136274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885412","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-04-20","<p>The Government made a firm commitment in its 2017 manifesto to retain the traditional method of voting by pencil and paper.</p><p> </p><p>The introduction of online voting would require very careful consideration and the Government currently has no plans to introduce or pilot online voting. There are concerns that electronic voting, by any means, is not seen by many to be suitably rigorous and secure, and could be vulnerable to attack or fraud.</p><p> </p><p>However, we remain interested to hear about the responses received by the Scottish and Welsh governments to their respective consultations on this issue.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-04-20T11:26:41.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885412/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885412/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-04-17","Electronic Voting: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether her Department has assessed the viability of online voting in Northern Ireland elections.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","136275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885413","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-25","<p>All Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) requests to use external contractor staff must be approved by the Chief Operating Officer during the on-going Civil Service-wide recruitment freeze. Our records show that only one request has been submitted to specifically bring in an external data analyst for a time-limited period over the last five years. This individual was recruited via the FCO’s managed service provider, Hays Recruitment. The FCO does not centrally hold data on the use of data collection companies. To provide this information would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>​</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-25T15:40:58.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885413/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885413/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-17","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which (a) external data analysts and (b) data collection companies his Department has used in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","136276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885414","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-25","<p>We are concerned about the recent church closures in Algeria. Our Embassy in Algeria has been in touch with the Protestant Church of Algeria, most recently on 20 February. The Minister responsible for Human Rights and I met with a delegation of Algerian Christians this week. The Protestant Church of Algeria has raised the closures with the Algerian Ministry of Interior. We stand ready to raise the subject with the Algerian authorities, should the Protestant Church of Algeria wish us to do so. The promotion and protection of freedom of religion or belief is an important priority for this Government. The Minister responsible for human rights , discussed the importance of Freedom of Religion or Belief with the Algerian Minister of Religious Affairs in October 2017, our Ambassador to Algeria followed up this conversation, with the Minister for Religious Affairs, in January.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-04-25T15:14:27.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885414/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885414/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-17","Algeria: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations his Department has made to the Algerian Government on the closure of places of Christian worship in that country.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","136277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885415","Department for Education","false","2018-04-26","<p>Religious Education (RE) is important to the Department and is mandatory in all state funded schools.</p><p> </p><p>Funding for subject knowledge enhancement (SKE) training supports universities and schools in recruiting to initial teacher training places in priority subjects. Although funding for SKE does not extend to RE, the Department has protected the bursaries for trainees in RE this year, in recognition of the recruitment challenges faced. Funding is also being continued for schools offering School Direct (salaried) places in RE. Teacher supply modelling, and the financial incentives that support teacher training, are reviewed on an annual basis.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-04-26T16:56:01.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885415/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885415/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885415/answer/previousversion/54113","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons his Department does not offer a subject knowledge enhancement grant to people training as religious education teachers; and if he will take steps to offer such grants for people wishing to train as teachers in that subject.","false","Biography information for Liz Twist","Blaydon","Liz Twist","136278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885416","Department for Education","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) is the lead regulator on managing asbestos and publishes guidance on effective and safe management of asbestos in line with the Control of Asbestos Regulations 2012.</p><p> </p><p>The Statutory Framework for the Early Years Foundation Stage requires providers to keep children safe, ensure premises are fit for purpose, are able manage any risks and undertake risk assessments to identify aspects of the environment that need to be checked on a regular basis or be removed or minimised. Providers must comply with requirements of Health and Safety legislation.</p><p> </p><p>The responsibility for managing asbestos in a building rests with the ‘duty holder’. The duty holder being the ‘person or organisation that has clear responsibility for the maintenance or repair of non-domestic premises.’ Duty holders are required to survey their building, create a register of Asbestos Containing Materials (ACMs) and write a management plan detailing the procedures for monitoring the condition of ACMs.</p><p>The department publishes guidance (‘Asbestos Management in Schools’) that would be relevant for early years provision in schools and could be applicable for a range of settings. This is intended to help duty holders understand their obligations and to support the effective management of asbestos.</p><p> </p><p>The HSE advice remains that as long as asbestos-containing materials are undamaged, and not in locations where they are vulnerable to damage, they should be managed in situ.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-23T16:59:13.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885416/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885416/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Schools: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what advice his Department provides to early years settings on (a) identifying and (b) removing asbestos from premises.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","136279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885417","Department for International Trade","false","2018-04-25","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) is a department for the whole of the UK. It supports exports from, and encourages investment to England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland - with the purpose of ensuring the benefits of trade and investment are spread across the whole of the UK.</p><p>DIT works closely with Invest Northern Ireland (INI) to support FDI into Northern Ireland, and to enable INI's expansion into 10 new markets this year. Of the 10 new overseas offices that INI have established, 8 are co located at British diplomatic missions abroad.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-04-25T16:29:03.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885417/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885417/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-04-17","Foreign Investment in UK: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions he has had with Invest Northern Ireland on the use of UK Embassies to promote Northern Ireland as a location for foreign direct investment.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","136280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885418","Department for International Trade","false","2018-04-25","<p>The Department for International Trade was formed in July 2016.</p><p>Since then, the Department's Trade Policy has grown from around 45 staff to approximately 500 staff, bringing together trade policy and country specialists, as well as economic analysts, lawyers, and research experts.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-04-25T16:59:23.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885418/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885418/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-04-17","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many people were employed in his Department dealing with trade negotiations in (a) March 2016 and (b) March 2018.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","136281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885419","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>No diplomatic staff of the Russian Federation are posted in locations in the UK outside London. However the Russia Federation has a Consulate General in Edinburgh with accredited consular staff.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-23T15:48:18.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885419/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885419/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-17","Russia: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many diplomats of the Russian Federation in the UK are based in locations outside London.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","136282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885420","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-25","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has not made a formal assessment of the fairness of the 2018 Presidential election. We note criticism of the constraints on the democratic space in Egypt. The Arab League and African Union sent observers to monitor the elections. The Prime Minister called President Sisi on 4 April and congratulated him on the chance he now has to take Egypt further along the path of democratic transition during his final term in office. The UK wants Egypt to succeed as a stable, prosperous and democratic country, building on the rights and freedoms set out in the 2014 Constitution.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-04-25T16:55:16.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885420/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885420/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-17","Egypt: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the fairness of the 2018 Egyptian Presidential election.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","136283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885421","Home Office","false","2018-04-19","<p>The Home Office is not required to hold this information. It is for Local Authorities in England to consider where support under the Children’s Act should be provided where the parents are subject to immigration conditions that restrict access to public funds.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-19T16:37:42.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885421/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885421/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Immigrants: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department holds information on the number of families with no recourse to public funds who have been offered support under Section 17 of the Children's Act 1989 in (a) Lewisham Deptford constituency, (b) London and (c) England in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","136284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885422","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes information on the primary roles that police officers perform, as well as the number of frontline officers, for police force areas in England and Wales. These data are published annually as part of the 'police workforce, England and Wales' statistical bulletin, the latest of which can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>Data on the primary roles officers perform, and the number of officers on the frontline, are collected at police force area level only, and cannot be broken down any further. Furthermore, the number of officers specifically on foot patrol cannot be separately identified in the data. The latest available data on frontline officers, broken down by police force area and going back to 2010, can be found in Table_F5 of the data tables accompanying the main release.</p><p> </p><p>Data for the years 2010 to 2014 are estimated since data prior to 31 March 2015 were collected under a different framework, with different definitions.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on the size and deployment of the police workforce are operational matters for Chief Officers working with their Police and Crime Commissioners and taking into account local priorities.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-04-23T17:01:58.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885422/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885422/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Police Patrolling: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police officers conducted street patrols in (a) Lewisham and (b) London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","136285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885423","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>A range of staple gluten free foods continue to be available on prescription for all patients with established gluten sensitivity enteropathies, including coeliac disease.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-23T15:13:55.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885423/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885423/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-17","Coeliac Disease: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether the Government plans to reintroduce prescriptions for gluten-free products for children who have coeliac disease.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","136286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885424","Home Office","false","2018-04-19","<p>Leave to remain in the UK is normally granted with a condition that prevents the person and their dependants from receiving welfare assistance from public funds. However, where the person qualifies for leave to remain on grounds related to their family or private life the condition is lifted if they or they or their dependent children would otherwise be destitute.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, children with no recourse to public funds are not precluded from support from a local authority under section 17 of the Children Act 1989. Assessment of the level of support needed is built into these provisions and will vary according to circumstances. The level of support provided under section 17 depends on the local authority’s assessment of the child’s needs.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-19T16:38:28.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885424/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885424/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Immigrants: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has made any recent assessment of the adequacy of support available to the children of parents with no recourse to public funds.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","136287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885425","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-23","<p>At a Westminster Hall Debate last year, the Rt Hon John Hayes MP announced the formation of a Task and Finish group to consider any regulatory issues and remedies. The group’s remit includes considering a range of matters such as cross-border hiring of taxis and private hire vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>The group is expected to submit its report shortly.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-04-23T16:31:18.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885425/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885425/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-04-17","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to prohibit the practice of cross-border hiring by private hire vehicles; and if he will bring forward legislative proposals to introduce a statutory definition of cross-border hiring.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","136288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885426","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-04","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be collated at disproportionate cost.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-04T13:47:23.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885426/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885426/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-17","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which (a) external data analysts and (b) data collection companies his Department has used in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","136289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885427","Department for International Development","false","2018-04-24","<p>This information is not held centrally within the department.</p><p>Details of all DFID’s contracts with suppliers above the OJEU threshold are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at: <a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</a>. Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a>.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-04-24T14:39:31.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885427/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885427/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-04-17","Department for International Development: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which (a) external data analysts and (b) data collection companies her Department has used in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","136290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885428","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-27","<p>Assuming the term “data collection companies” is primarily aimed at firms which have developed or maintained some kind of database to which BEIS has access; the following list of company subscriptions have been taken out or renewed since the start of FY17/18:</p><p> </p><p>BankSearch; BDRC Continental; Beauhurst; BoardEx; Capital IQ; Crunchbase; Dun &amp; Bradstreet; Experian; GTAP; ICIS; IHS Markitt; Manifest; Navigant; Pitchbook; Springwise.</p><p> </p><p>If the “collection” term is widened to more general activities then this would encompass many more companies including Ipsos MORI, NATCEN, Neisr, Mint UK (Bureau van Dijk) etc.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-04-27T13:55:12.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885428/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885428/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-04-17","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which (a) external data analysts and (b) data collection companies his Department has used in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","136291"
