"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885431","Women and Equalities","false","2018-05-02","<p>The previous Home Secretary and the Speaker have corresponded and a decision will be made in due course.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-05-02T10:48:31.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885431/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885431/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-04-17","Access to Elected Office for Disabled People Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what correspondence there has been between her Department and the Speaker of the House of Commons on whether a decision to re-open the Access to Elected Office scheme has been made.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","136294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885432","Department for Education","false","2018-04-23","<p>The findings in the Stop Start report are estimates based on analysis of different datasets and a snapshot survey of local councils. Local councils currently supply data on children’s centre provision through the Department for Education’s ‘Get Information about Schools’ (GIAS) database at <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>. Statutory guidance says that local councils should update their children’s centre data on a regular basis to reflect any changes to provision. We believe that the GIAS database is the most efficient and proportionate method for local councils to report children’s centre closures on a regular basis. As set out in legislation, local councils have responsibility for determining precisely what services are delivered through children’s centres. We believe that this is the right approach.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","136299","2018-04-23T16:49:00.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885432/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885432/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Children's Centres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to Stop Start, published by the Sutton Trust on 16 April 2018, if he will make an assessment on the implications for his policies on the recording of sure start centre closures as a result of the findings in that report.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","136295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885433","Treasury","false","2018-04-24","<p>The majority of parents apply for Tax-Free Childcare without any issues. For the small number of parents that have a technical problem applying for Tax-Free Childcare the majority of these are caused by:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>delayed eligibility responses, caused by the application effectively becoming stuck at some point in the IT system;</p></li><li><p>issues with children incorrectly duplicating on the system which is caused by the interaction between HMRC and NS&amp;I IT systems; and</p></li><li><p>parents seeing error screens during their application which have a number of root causes.</p><p> </p><p>Following work by HMRC to improve the childcare service and fix these problems, over 99% of parents now receive an eligibility response within 5 working days, only a small number of parents are experiencing a duplicate child issue and the number of parents seeing an error screen at some point through their application, has reduced to less than 2%.</p><p> </p></li></ul>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-04-24T12:49:49.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885433/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885433/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-17","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to his Answer of 16 April 2018 to Question 134639, on Children: Day Care, what the technical issues were that were experienced by parents when applying for tax-free childcare through the online service; and what caused those issues.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","136296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885434","Cabinet Office","false","2018-04-26","<p>The National Security Communications Team is already in operation. Its purpose is to allow government to better tackle the communications elements of interconnected complex challenges to our national security, including (but not limited to) disinformation.</p><p>This work differs to that of the Rapid Response Unit which has been recently launched based in No10 &amp; the Cabinet Office, as part of the Government Communications Service (GCS) with the remit to expand existing digital analysis (including, but not limited to, misinformation and disinformation) and content capability to communicate public information that is accurate, clear and responsive.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-04-26T11:30:43.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885434/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885434/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-04-17","Disinformation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the planned effective operational date is for the Government's dedicated national security unit to tackle fake news and disinformation.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","136297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885435","Cabinet Office","false","2018-04-26","<p>The National Security Communications Team is expanding in capacity on the recommendations of the National Security Capability Review, published on the 28 March. The enhanced capability provided by the unit will ensure Government has the right mix of skills and expertise to use communications as a lever to support key national security objectives, and allow Government to better tackle the interconnected complex challenges to our national security, including (but not limited to) disinformation.</p><p>Recruitment to the National Security team is ongoing.</p><p>This work differs to that of the Rapid Response Unit which has been recently launched as a six-month pilot, based in No10 &amp; the Cabinet Office, as part of the Government Communications Service (GCS) with the remit to expand existing digital analysis (including, but not limited to, misinformation and disinformation) and content capability to communicate public information that is accurate, clear and responsive.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-04-26T11:27:28.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885435/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885435/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-04-17","Disinformation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the staffing complement is by grade of the Government's dedicated national security unit to tackle fake news and disinformation.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","136298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885436","Department for Education","false","2018-04-23","<p>The findings in the Stop Start report are estimates based on analysis of different datasets and a snapshot survey of local councils. Local councils currently supply data on children’s centre provision through the Department for Education’s ‘Get Information about Schools’ (GIAS) database at <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>. Statutory guidance says that local councils should update their children’s centre data on a regular basis to reflect any changes to provision. We believe that the GIAS database is the most efficient and proportionate method for local councils to report children’s centre closures on a regular basis. As set out in legislation, local councils have responsibility for determining precisely what services are delivered through children’s centres. We believe that this is the right approach.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","136295","2018-04-23T16:49:00.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885436/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885436/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to Stop Start, published by the Sutton Trust on 16 April 2018, if he will make an assessment of the potential benefits of introducing a national register of children’s centres which sets minimum levels of Sure Start provision.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","136299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885437","Home Office","false","2018-05-02","<p>Information about individuals who have been denied or charged for NHS treatment is not held by the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>Individuals affected should contact the Home Office. The new team set up will help the applicants to demonstrate that they are entitled to live in the UK and will aim to resolve cases within two weeks when the evidence has been provided.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office will also be setting up a new compensation scheme. We will want to take time to consult on the scope of the new scheme.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-02T12:43:01.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885437/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885437/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Immigration: Caribbean","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the number of Windrush citizens who have been (a) denied and (b) charged for NHS treatment; and what steps she is taking together with the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care to rectify that matter.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","136300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885438","Department for Education","false","2018-04-23","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Batley and Spen to the answers given by the former Minister of State for Children and Families (Robert Goodwill) on 12 December 2017 to question 118316: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=118316" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=118316</a>. And on 19 December 2017 to question 118701: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=118701" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=118701</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-23T16:56:40.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885438/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885438/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he plans to conduct a consultation on children's centres.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","136301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885439","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>The new contract will run for 11.5 years. Costs will be considerably lower than the current contract, with the savings delivered over the lifetime of the contract. This underlines our commitment to deliver value for money to our passport customers and the tax payer.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the procurement process, all bidders were evaluated against their individual pricing proposal. Proposals relating to unsuccessful bids are commercially sensitive, and therefore no evidence relating to differences between the bids will be published.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-23T09:10:21.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885439/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885439/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Passports: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to her Answer of 16 April 2018 to Question 904765, Official Report, column 21, if she will publish (a) the evidential basis for the contract for the printing of passports being estimated as saving £120 million and (b) details of that proposed contract; over what time period those savings are estimated to accrue; and what proportion of the cost of the contract those estimated savings represent.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","136302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885440","Home Office","false","2018-04-30","<p>The Home Office does not hold centrally the information requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office collects and publishes information on the number of persons detained under the Mental Health Act 1983, including information on where the person is detained, and whether they are under 18 or aged 18 years and over, at police force area level only.</p><p> </p><p>These data were collected on a mandatory basis for the first time in 2016/17, and are published as part of the ‘Police powers and procedures, England and Wales’ statistical bulletin, which can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2017</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Figures for the period 2014/15 and 2015/16 were published by the National Police Chiefs’ Council and can be accessed using the following links:</p><p><a href="http://www.npcc.police.uk/documents/edhr/2015/Section%20136%20MHA%20201415%20Data.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.npcc.police.uk/documents/edhr/2015/Section%20136%20MHA%20201415%20Data.pdf</a></p><p><a href="http://www.npcc.police.uk/documents/S136%20Data%202015%2016.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.npcc.police.uk/documents/S136%20Data%202015%2016.pdf</a></p><p>Data are not available for previous years.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office does not hold this information for individual London boroughs.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-04-30T14:12:47.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885440/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885440/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Police Custody: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on the number of children living in the London Borough of Lewisham who spent time in a police station as a place of safety as a result of a mental health condition in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","136303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885441","Home Office","false","2018-04-19","<p>The information requested could only be supplied at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Home Office data is not broken down by Parliamentary constituency or metropolitan borough. The latest data, which goes back to 2009, is published in ‘Immigration Statistics, October to December 2017’, and is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/681703/detention-oct-dec-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/681703/detention-oct-dec-2017-tables.ods</a>.</p><p>There is no process of appeal against detention decisions, but detainees are able to apply to a judge of the First-tier Tribunal for bail, as many times as they wish. They are also able to challenge the lawfulness of detention via judicial review or writ of <em>habeas corpus</em>.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-19T16:39:16.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885441/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885441/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-17","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people living in (a) Lewisham Deptford constituency and (b) the London Borough of Lewisham have (i) been detained for immigration purposes and (ii) successfully appealed a Home Office decision to detain them for immigration purposes in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","136304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885442","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>The Department does collect, via the school census, figures for the number of children on the schools admission register at three points during each academic year, but this will not provide a full or accurate indication of the numbers of pupils removed from the school register.</p><p>The grounds on which a pupil’s name can be lawfully deleted from a school’s admission register are prescribed in regulation 8 of the Education (Pupil Registration) (England) Regulations 2006 as amended.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-04-24T14:18:47.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885442/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885442/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-17","Secondary Education: Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many secondary school children have been off-rolled by their school in (a) the London Borough of Lewisham, (b) London and (c) England in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","136305"
